      },
      {
        "from": "Order Enrichment Service",
        "to": "CustomerService",
        "status": "risk",
        "issue": "Same outbound timeout issue: 1000ms timeout vs 150ms p99. A single slow CustomerService call can exhaust the upstream caller's 500ms budget."
      },
      {
        "from": "Order Enrichment Service",
        "to": "InventoryService",
        "status": "broken",
        "issue": "CRITICAL: InventoryService p99 of 800ms alone exceeds the 500ms inbound timeout. Even if called first and alone, this service will cause upstream timeouts at p99. Being called third (sequentially), the minimum time before this call starts is ~0ms (best case) but typically p50 of Product+Customer. This call will almost never complete within the upstream budget."
      }
    ],
    "contract_compliance": "VIOLATED. The service cannot meet its implicit SLA with the upstream caller. The 500ms inbound timeout is a contract: 'I will respond within 500ms.' Sequential calls with a combined p99 of 1150ms make this contract impossible to honor at tail latencies. Even at median latencies, InventoryService alone is likely to consume most of the 500ms budget.",
    "data_flow_integrity": "Data flow logic (receive event, enrich from 3 sources, return) is sound in principle. The problem is entirely in timing: enriched responses will be discarded by the upstream caller because they arrive after the 500ms deadline. The work is done but wasted."
  },

  "observability_review": {
    "logging": {
      "coverage": "adequate",
      "gaps": [
        "No mention of logging upstream timeout events — when the caller disconnects at 500ms, does the service log that the response was orphaned?",
        "No mention of logging which specific downstream call was in-flight when the upstream timeout occurred"
      ]
    },
